ce:section.ce:para:
To determine the elemental composition and chemical states of the carbon dot, the binding properties of the samples were further verified by X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS), as shown in Fig. 2
                     (a)(b). The C1s spectrum of ACD from 282.0 to 295.0eV was fitted to extract the components of the peaks (Table 1
                     ), which could be assigned to the sp2 CC, sp3 CC, CO/COC, CO/OCO, and π–π* bonds [31]. The ratio of the CC to π–π* transition bonds is related to the crystallinity. This ratio was higher for sample ACD than for GCA, which is consistent with the TEM results. The portion of the CO bond is increased with the functional group on carbon dot edges and the activation partly destroyed the structural order of the sample. In general, the conductivity increases with decreasing concentration of surface oxygen functional groups. However, the electrical conductivity of ACD was observed to be higher than that of GCA (1.6 S cm-1) even though they contained similar concentration of oxygen (Table 2
                     ). More recently, the excellent electrical conductivity of carbon dots was characterized by Bhattacharjee et al. [27,32].
